{
  "text": "\"Classification criteria should not be interdependent\" Furthermore, they should be carefully defined, with variables independent of each other, totally inclusive, mutually exclusive, and clinically relevant. Epidemiological studies show us that the most common disease within the systemic rheumatic diseases is primary Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome (SS), followed by rheumatoid arthritis. For primary SS, no international or American College of Rheumatology (ACR) classification set of criteria exists and as the time from a patient's first symptom to diagnosis is 7-9 years, it seems obvious that a new set of classification criteria is needed to add to the seven different sets of criteria produced during the past 25 years. [CITATION_1] A look at articles published in English within this field shows that the European criteria from 1993 or 1996 2 3 are the ones most commonly cited, while the Copenhagen criteria 4 are used in China and, seemingly, the ones most used world wide.",
